rth America during the ensuing six-year period, possibly reaching a million listeners. Drawing on a memoir by member Henry Albrecht, Newman provides insights into the musicians'desire to bring their music to the audiences of a democratic republic at this turbulent time. Eager to avoid the egotism and self-promotion of the European patronage system, they pledged to work for their mutual interests both musically and socially. "One for all, and all for one" became their motto. Originally published in German, Albrecht's memoir is presented here in for the first time in translation. Nancy Newman is Associate Professor in the Music Department at the University at Albany, SUNY.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForty-Eighters (American immigrants). 0aSymphony orchestraszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAmerican musical life.  aClassical music.  aGermania Musical Society.  aHenry Albrecht.  aInstrumental works.  aMusic performances.  aRevolutions of 1848.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580467681?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580467681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580467681/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles